bout 1352","1328":"1328","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wakeman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>wakeman</i> ‘watchman, town guard’, also ‘municipal officer responsible for night-time security and the town musicians’. <i>Wakeman</i> was the title of the chief magistrate of the borough of Ripon until 1604, when it was changed to mayor. He was the head of the body of wakemen whose duty was to blow a cow's horn every night at nine o'clock. If between then and sunrise any burglary took place, it was made good at the public charge. See also   Watchman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Watchman","meanings":["Native American (Navajo): from English <i>watchman</i>, probably used as a translation of a Navajo term for this occupation, <i>ha'asídí</i>.","English and Scottish: occupational name from Middle English <i>waccheman</i> ‘watchman, guard, sentry’, also used as a nickname for a person characterised by wakefulness. Compare   Wakeman  ."]},{"name":"Watchorn","meanings":["English (East Midlands, especially Leicestershire): nickname apparently from Middle English <i>wache</i> ‘vigil, wake, watch’ (Old English <i>wacce</i>) + <i>horn</i> ‘horn’. Compare the discussion of   Wakeman  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":62,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Wakeman was born in 1320, in Worcestershire, England, his father, William WAKEMAN, was 25 and his mother, Isabelle Hastings, was 21. He married Diana Cortwright in 1352, in Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1320–":"1320–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1380–1460":"1380–1460","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1352":"1352","1440":"1440","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1337":"1337","1347":"1347","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","about 1352":"umbes 1352","1328":"1328","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Engla